manual_description: The capital of India, New Delhi, is a land of intense contrasts. It has the Imperial charm and regal pomp of the historic Red Fort and the massive Rashtrapati Bhawan, the world-class opulence of the Taj Mahal Hotel, Old Delhi, and the frenetic energy of Connaught Place. Modern Delhi also offers an array of sights and experiences, from discotheques to puppet shows, from dosa to curry, and the National Gallery of Modern Art.
place_description: New Delhi is the capital of India and a part of the National Capital Territory of Delhi. New Delhi is the seat of all three branches of the Government of India, hosting the Rashtrapati Bhavan, Sansad Bhavan, and the Supreme Court. Wikipedia.

top_attractions.prev_detail_description:
Rajpath (Kingsway) is a vast parade linking India Gate to the offices of the Indian government. Built on an imperial scale between 1914 and 1931, it was designed by Edwin Lutyens and Herbert Baker and underlined the ascendance of the British rulers. Yet just 16 years later, the Brits were out on their ear and Indian politicians were pacing the corridors of power.
At the western end of Rajpath the official residence of the president of India, Rashtrapati Bhavan, now partially open to the public via guided tour, is flanked by the mirror-image, dome-crowned North Secretariat and South Secretariat. These house government ministries and are not open to the public. The Indian parliament meets nearby at the Sansad Bhavan, a circular, colonnaded edifice at the end of Sansad Marg, also not open to the public.At Rajpath’s eastern end is mighty India Gate. This 42m-high stone memorial arch, designed by Lutyens, pays tribute to around 90,000 Indian Army soldiers who died in WWI, the Northwest Frontier operations and the 1919 Anglo-Afghan War.
top_attractions.detail_description: Rajpath is a grand, tree-lined boulevard in New Delhi, stretching from Rashtrapati Bhavan to India Gate. It hosts national ceremonies and offers views of key government buildings and the iconic war memorial arch.
top_attractions.name: Rajpath

top_attractions.prev_detail_description:
This glorious, if dusty, museum is full of treasures. Mind-bogglingly ancient, sophisticated figurines from the Harappan civilisation, almost 5000 years old, include the remarkable Dancing Girl, and there are also some fine ceramics from the even-older Nal civilisation. Other items include Buddha relics, exquisite jewellery, miniature paintings, medieval woodcarvings, textiles and musical instruments. Don't miss the immense, five-tier wooden temple chariot built in South India in the 19th century.
Allow at least two hours for a proper visit. Bring your passport to obtain an audio guide (included in the foreigner ticket price; ₹150 extra for Indian tourists). There's also a cheap-as-chips cafe inside the museum gates and round to the left. You don't have to visit the museum to use the cafe; handy because eating options are limited round here.
top_attractions.detail_description: Explore ancient artifacts from the Harappan and Nal civilizations, Buddha relics, jewelry, paintings, and a 19th-century wooden temple chariot. Audio guides available with passport. Spend at least two hours discovering India's rich history.
top_attractions.name: National Museum

In the basement is an impressive collection of oil portraits of former viceroys, governors general and British monarchs.
Opposite, in the former presidential stables, is a more old-fashioned collection of gifts given to former presidents by visiting dignitaries. You must pre-book your visit online, paying in advance as you do so.

top_attractions.prev_detail_description:
In the residence of controversial former prime minister Indira Gandhi is this interesting museum devoted to her life and her political-heavyweight family. It displays her personal effects, including the blood-stained sari she was wearing when she was assassinated in 1984; in the back garden a glass-covered pathway traces her final steps before she was shot and killed by two security guards. Many rooms in the house are preserved as they were, providing a window into the family's life.
An exhibit at the rear charts the life of Indira’s son, Rajiv, who met a similarly violent end when he was assassinated in 1991.

top_attractions.prev_detail_description:
This magnificent white-marble gurdwara (Sikh temple), topped by glinting golden onion domes, was constructed at the site where the eighth Sikh guru, Harkrishan Dev, stayed before his 1664 death. Despite his tender years, the six-year-old guru tended to victims of Delhi’s cholera and smallpox epidemic, and the waters of the large tank are said to have healing powers. It's full of colour and life, yet tranquil, and live devotional songs waft over the compound.
As at all gurdwaras, free meals are served to pilgrims daily. Just inside the entrance to the complex is a small museum, chronicling the history of Sikhism and its gurus and martyrs.

top_attractions.prev_detail_description:
Firozabad, the fifth city of Delhi, was built by Feroz Shah Tughlaq in 1354, the first city here to be built on the river. Only the fortress remains, with crumbling walls protecting the Jama Masjid (Friday mosque), a baoli (step-well), and the pyramid-like Hawa Mahal, topped by a 13m-high sandstone Ashoka Pillar inscribed with 3rd-century-BC Buddhist edicts. There’s an otherworldly atmosphere to the ruins.
Entrance is free after 2pm every Thursday when crowds gather at the mosque and other points of importance to light candles and incense and leave bowls of milk to appease Delhi’s djinns (invisible spirits), who are said to occupy the underground chambers beneath the ruins.Shoes should be removed when entering the mosque and Hawa Mahal.
top_attractions.detail_description: Explore the sandstone ruins of Feroz Shah Kotla fortress, featuring the Jama Masjid, a step-well, and the Ashoka Pillar. Visit Thursday afternoons to join locals in lighting candles and offerings to spirits beneath the site.
top_attractions.name: Feroz Shah Kotla

top_attractions.prev_detail_description:
On the banks of the Yamuna River, this peaceful, very well maintained park contains a simple black-marble platform marking the spot where Mahatma Gandhi was cremated following his assassination in 1948. This memorial is a thought-provoking spot, inscribed with what are said to have been Gandhi’s final words, Hai Ram ('Oh, God'). Every Friday (the day he died) commemorative prayers are held here at 5pm, as well as on 2 October and 30 January, his birth and death anniversaries.
Despite being perfect picnic territory, you're not allowed to bring food into the park, and there's nowhere to buy any once inside. Further north you'll find memorials commemorating where Jawaharlal Nehru, Indira Gandhi and Rajiv Gandhi were cremated.South from Raj Ghat, just across Kisan Ghat Rd, are some equally peaceful landscaped gardens containing Gandhi Darshan, a pavilion displaying photos relating to the Mahatma.

top_attractions.prev_detail_description: The extravagance of these glorious gardens is such that Louis Mountbatten, India’s last British viceroy, was said to have employed 418 gardeners. There are fountains, cypress, bougainvillea, climbing roses, symmetrical lawns and wandering peacocks. If you're in town when the gardens are in flower (the same months they're open), they're not to be missed. Security is strict; visitors must leave all bags, and even water bottles, at the cloakroom by the entrance.
top_attractions.detail_description: Mughal Gardens in New Delhi feature fountains, cypress, bougainvillea, climbing roses, and peacocks. Open during flowering months, the gardens showcase symmetrical lawns and strict security with no bags allowed inside.

top_attractions.prev_detail_description: Much of this lovely museum is outside, including tree-shaded carvings and life-size examples of village huts from various regions of India. Displays celebrate the traditional crafts of India, with some beautiful textiles on display indoors, such as embroidery from Kashmir and cross-stitch from Punjab. Highlights include a huge wooden 18th-century temple chariot from Maharashtra. Artisans sell their products in the rear courtyard. The museum also includes the excellent Cafe Lota and a very good shop.
top_attractions.detail_description: Explore traditional Indian crafts at this open-air museum featuring village huts, folk art, textiles, and an 18th-century wooden temple chariot. Shop handmade goods and enjoy local cuisine at Cafe Lota.
top_attractions.name: Crafts Museum

seasonal.March to May: Spring transitions into summer during these months, with temperatures gradually rising. March offers mild weather, while April and May can be quite hot, with temperatures soaring above 40°C (104°F). This is a great time to visit gardens and parks, such as the Lodhi Gardens, and to experience the vibrant Holi festival in March, which celebrates the arrival of spring.
seasonal.June to August: The monsoon season brings relief from the heat, with heavy rainfall occurring from June to August. While the weather can be humid and unpredictable, the city transforms into a lush green landscape. This is a quieter time for tourism, but visitors can enjoy fewer crowds at popular attractions and experience the local culture more intimately.
seasonal.Travel Tip: When visiting New Delhi, it's advisable to dress modestly, especially when visiting religious sites. Use public transport like the Delhi Metro for convenient travel around the city. Always stay hydrated, and be cautious of street food; opt for popular stalls with high turnover to ensure freshness.
seasonal.Overview: New Delhi, the capital of India, is a vibrant city that blends history, culture, and modernity. Known for its stunning architecture, bustling markets, and rich heritage, it offers a unique experience for travelers. From historical landmarks like the Red Fort and India Gate to contemporary attractions like the Lotus Temple, New Delhi is a city that caters to diverse interests.
seasonal.December to February: The winter months in New Delhi are characterized by cool and pleasant weather, making it an ideal time for sightseeing. Daytime temperatures range from 10°C to 20°C (50°F to 68°F). Visitors can explore outdoor attractions comfortably, attend cultural festivals, and enjoy the festive atmosphere during Christmas and New Year celebrations.
seasonal.Regional Highlights: New Delhi is home to several UNESCO World Heritage Sites, including the Qutub Minar and Humayun's Tomb. The bustling markets of Chandni Chowk offer a taste of local life, while the upscale Connaught Place provides a modern shopping experience. Don't miss the chance to visit the National Museum and the Gandhi Smriti for a deeper understanding of India's history.
seasonal.September to November: As the monsoon recedes, the weather becomes more pleasant, making it a popular time for tourists. September and October are marked by mild temperatures and clear skies, perfect for exploring the city. The festival of Diwali, celebrated in October or November, lights up the city with festivities, making it a magical time to visit.

travelInfo.🌞 Best Time to Visit: The ideal time to visit New Delhi is from October to March when the weather is pleasant. Avoid the summer months, as temperatures can soar.
travelInfo.🕌 Must-Visit Landmarks: Don't miss iconic sites like the Red Fort, India Gate, and Qutub Minar. Each landmark offers a glimpse into India's rich history and architectural marvels.
travelInfo.Conclusion: With its rich culture and vibrant atmosphere, New Delhi promises an unforgettable experience. Embrace the adventure and enjoy every moment of your visit!
travelInfo.🛍️ Shopping Hotspots: Explore markets like Chandni Chowk for traditional goods and Dilli Haat for handicrafts. Bargaining is common, so don't hesitate to negotiate prices.
travelInfo.👗 Cultural Etiquette: Dress modestly, especially when visiting religious sites. It's respectful to cover shoulders and knees, and removing shoes is often required.
travelInfo.🍽️ Local Cuisine: Indulge in Delhi's diverse culinary scene, from street food like chaat to fine dining experiences. Be sure to try local favorites such as butter chicken and parathas.
travelInfo.Introduction: New Delhi, the vibrant capital of India, is a city that beautifully blends history and modernity. Before you embark on your journey, here are some essential tips to enhance your experience and navigate the bustling streets with ease.
travelInfo.🏨 Accommodation Options: New Delhi offers a range of accommodations, from luxury hotels to budget hostels. Research and book in advance to find the best deals.
travelInfo.💧 Staying Hydrated: The climate can be quite dry, so drink plenty of water throughout the day. Always opt for bottled water to avoid any health issues.
travelInfo.🚕 Transportation Tips: Public transport is efficient, with options like the metro and auto-rickshaws. However, be prepared for traffic and consider using ride-sharing apps for convenience.

travelInfo.🚲 Bicycles: Cycling is becoming increasingly popular in New Delhi, with dedicated bike lanes in some areas. Renting a bicycle can be a fun way to see the city at a leisurely pace, especially in parks and quieter neighborhoods.
travelInfo.🚖 Taxis & Ride-Sharing: Taxis and ride-sharing services like Uber and Ola are widely available in New Delhi. They provide a convenient way to travel, especially for longer distances or when public transport is less accessible.
travelInfo.🚌 Buses: Delhi's bus network is extensive and covers many areas of the city. While it can be crowded and challenging for newcomers, it is an economical option for those looking to explore on a budget.
travelInfo.Conclusion: With a variety of transportation options available, getting around New Delhi can be both easy and enjoyable. Embrace the adventure and choose the mode of transport that best suits your needs!
travelInfo.🚗 Car Rentals: Renting a car can be a good option for those who prefer to travel at their own pace. However, be prepared for heavy traffic and the challenges of driving in a bustling city like New Delhi.
travelInfo.Introduction: Getting around in New Delhi can be an exciting adventure, with a variety of transportation options available to explore the vibrant city. From the bustling streets to the efficient metro system, navigating New Delhi offers both convenience and cultural experiences.
travelInfo.🚇 Metro System: The Delhi Metro is one of the most efficient and affordable ways to travel around the city. With extensive coverage and frequent services, it connects major attractions and neighborhoods, making it a popular choice for both locals and tourists.
travelInfo.🚶 Walking: Walking is a great way to experience the local culture and discover hidden gems in New Delhi. Many areas, especially markets and historical sites, are best explored on foot.
travelInfo.🛵 Auto Rickshaws: Auto rickshaws are a popular mode of transport in New Delhi, offering a unique and fun way to navigate the city. They are ideal for short trips and can easily weave through traffic.
travelInfo.🚌 Hop-On Hop-Off Buses: For tourists, hop-on hop-off buses provide a convenient way to see major attractions at your own pace. These buses allow you to explore the city while providing informative commentary along the route.
travelInfo.🚄 Trains: In addition to the metro, there are intercity trains that connect New Delhi to other major cities. These trains can be a comfortable and scenic way to travel longer distances.
